  "market_context": "Strong uptrend in NQ1! with consecutive higher highs and higher lows; RSI remained above 70 for extended period, indicating sustained bullish momentum.",
  "key_observation": "The analyst emphasized that in strong trends, RSI can stay overbought (above 70) for a long time, and interpreting overbought as a short signal is a critical mistake.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Identified the market as being in a clear uptrend by observing higher highs and higher lows on the NQ1! 15-minute chart.",
    "Step 2: Pointed out that RSI was overbought (above 70) for an extended duration—specifically near timestamps 16–17 and 20–21—yet price kept rising.",
    "Step 3: Simulated a trader entering a short at the first overbought RSI point (around timestamp 16–17), only to see price explode higher on the next candle, causing a loss.",
    "Step 4: Simulated a second short entry at a later extreme RSI high (near timestamp 20.5), where RSI peaked and a red candle appeared, but price still continued grinding upward violently."
  ],
  "outcome": "Loss — both hypothetical short entries resulted in immediate adverse price movement and losses.",
  "lessons": "Do not treat RSI overbought/oversold levels as standalone trade signals; in strong trends, RSI can remain extreme for prolonged periods—always confirm with trend context and price structure.",
